{"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"]},"docs":[{"location":"","title":"Welcome to MkDocs","text":"<p>For full documentation visit mkdocs.org.</p>"},{"location":"#commands","title":"Commands","text":"<ul> <li><code>mkdocs new [dir-name]</code> - Create a new project.</li> <li><code>mkdocs serve</code> - Start the live-reloading docs server.</li> <li><code>mkdocs build</code> - Build the documentation site.</li> <li><code>mkdocs -h</code> - Print help message and exit.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"#project-layout","title":"Project layout","text":"<pre><code>mkdocs.yml    # The configuration file.\ndocs/\n    index.md  # The documentation homepage.\n    ...       # Other markdown pages, images and other files.\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"intro/","title":"TNC World","text":"<p>A compact, narrative-focused tabletop roleplaying game about exploration, conflict, and small groups forced to make hard choices in a changing world.</p>"},{"location":"intro/#overview","title":"Overview","text":"<p>TNC World is a rules-light system that centers on character motives, player-driven scenes, and fast resolution. Emphasis is on story beats and consequences rather than simulation: tense choices, risky plans, and the social costs of survival.</p>"},{"location":"intro/#what-you-need","title":"What you need","text":"<ul> <li>1 Gamemaster (GM) and 2\u20136 players  </li> <li>1\u20132 six-sided dice (d6) per player (or a dice pool app)  </li> <li>Character sheets (one per player)  </li> <li>Tokens or markers for resource tracking  </li> </ul>"},{"location":"intro/#core-themes","title":"Core themes","text":"<ul> <li>Survival vs. Ethics: tradeoffs between doing what's needed and who you become doing it  </li> <li>Small-group dynamics: leadership, trust, and betrayal under pressure  </li> <li>Mystery of the world: fragments to discover, consequences to unwrap</li> </ul>"},{"location":"intro/#how-to-play-quick","title":"How to play (quick)","text":"<ol> <li>Create characters: pick a role, a driving desire, and one secret.  </li> <li>The GM frames a scene and prompts player actions.  </li> <li>Players declare an action and roll d6 (simple success/failure or use a small pool).  </li> <li>GM describes results and advances threats or rewards.  </li> <li>Track resources and complications; use short downtime between scenes to develop characters.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"intro/#safety-and-session-zero","title":"Safety and session zero","text":"<ul> <li>Run a short session zero to set tone, boundaries, and consent.  </li> <li>Use safety tools (X-card, lines &amp; veils) and establish hard limits.  </li> <li>Agree on the level of violence, horror, and mature themes beforehand.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"intro/#for-the-gm","title":"For the GM","text":"<ul> <li>Start small: one clear objective and one strong antagonist.  </li> <li>Keep scenes short and move the spotlight between players.  </li> <li>Use complications to force meaningful choices rather than arbitrary penalties.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"intro/#next-steps","title":"Next steps","text":"<ul> <li>Read the rules reference for character generation, mechanics, and combat.  </li> <li>Try a one-shot scenario to learn pacing and flow.  </li> <li>Share feedback and house rules with your table.</li> </ul> <p>(Copyright: You may copy and adapt this document for personal and playtest use.)</p>"}]}
=======
{"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"]},"docs":[{"location":"","title":"Welcome to MkDocs","text":"<p>For full documentation visit mkdocs.org.</p>"},{"location":"#commands","title":"Commands","text":"<ul> <li><code>mkdocs new [dir-name]</code> - Create a new project.</li> <li><code>mkdocs serve</code> - Start the live-reloading docs server.</li> <li><code>mkdocs build</code> - Build the documentation site.</li> <li><code>mkdocs -h</code> - Print help message and exit.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"#project-layout","title":"Project layout","text":"<pre><code>mkdocs.yml    # The configuration file.\ndocs/\n    index.md  # The documentation homepage.\n    ...       # Other markdown pages, images and other files.\n</code></pre> <p>test </p>"},{"location":"character-creation/","title":"Chapter 3: Character Creation","text":"<p>*\"Every Nomad starts with scars -- it's the ones you choose that define you.\"</p> <p>The character you play in The Nomad Chronicles may appear to be a series of numbers and mathematical formulae on a sheet of power. What it is, however, is your eyes and ears into the world.</p> <p>There are six steps to character creation, each one a straightforward extension from the step before it.</p> <p>Creation Steps Quick Reference</p> <ol> <li>Choose a Concept</li> <li>Determine Ability Scores</li> <li>Select a Background</li> <li>Choose Traits, Expertise, &amp; Specializations</li> <li>Pick or Purchase Equipment</li> <li>Finalize and Calculate Derived Stats (Health, Speed, Defense, etc)</li> </ol>"},{"location":"character-creation/#concept","title":"Step 1: Concept","text":"<p>Every character starts as an idea. Who they are, what drives them, and what kind of survivor they're on track to become.</p> Think in Arcs <p>Before numbers hit the page, think personality, motivation, and aesthetic.</p> <ul> <li> <p>What keeps this character moving?</p> </li> <li> <p>What broke them before the story began?</p> </li> <li> <p>How do they fit with the group?</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"character-creation/#ability-scores","title":"Step 2: Ability Scores","text":"<p>Ability Scores are the backbone of how your character moves and operates through the world, and are used to determine your character's physical and mental prowess.</p>"},{"location":"character-creation/#determining-abilities","title":"Determining Abilities","text":"<p>When you're ready, take your 3d6 and roll them, adding them together and comparing that result to the Determining Abilities Table. On the left side of that table are the various sum results of rolling 3d6. On the right side is where you'll find the Ability Scores you'll record on your sheet.</p> <p>You'll need to make six total rolls. One per Ability. You may roll in order, starting from the top.</p> <p>After rolling as standard, your GM may allow you to swap up to two Ability Scores of your choice, to better customize your concept.</p> GM Tip <p>Optional Ruling: Like in certain dungeon-crawling systems, you could also simply allow your players to roll six times, record the results, and apply those results to whichever Ability Scores they fancy for specific build types.</p> <p>Abilities Table</p> Roll Result Starting Ability 3 -2 4 -1 5 -1 6 0 7 0 8 0 9 1 10 1 11 1 12 2 13 2 14 2 15 3 16 3 17 4 18 4"},{"location":"character-creation/#exceptional-start","title":"Exceptional Start","text":"If, while rolling Ability Scores, a player rolls Doubles, they may add up to half of the value of their Chance Die to the result of their roll for determining their starting score. If they roll Triples, they may add up to the full value of their Chance Die to up to two different Ability Scores. No Ability Score can go above 6 at Character Creation in this way. GM-Tip (Scores above 5) <p>Any player that wants an Ability Score above 5 must first take at least 1 Infection Level to represent the Nano-Virus affecting that particular Score. 5 is peak human capacity.</p>"},{"location":"character-creation/#standard-array","title":"Standard Array","text":"<p>Instead of leaving their characters in the hands of fate with a roll, a player may wish to start play with a Standard Array of Ability Scores. There are two options in this particular setup, depending on how specialized or versatile a player would like their character to be.</p> Array 1 Array 2 +4 +3 +2 +3 +2 +2 +1 +1 0 0 -1 -1 <p>Understanding High Scores</p> <p>The pages below detail what having an Ability Score at certain values could mean for a character. A 0 is average, and is representative of any number of NPC capabilities. A 5 is peak capability for any human character, with any score above it counting as Super Human. No score can go above 5 without at least 1 point in Infection Level. A 10 is the game cap, and is a generally unheard of level of ability.</p>"},{"location":"character-creation/#background","title":"Step 3: Background","text":"<p>The seven Backgrounds available represent a wide swath of personal or professional inclinations and training. They encompass many common personal experiences and walks of life. They are balanced based on what individuals in those professions sociotypically encounter and work with in their everyday lives. If your table requires more specific experiences or options, be sure to discuss the particulars with your GM.</p> <p>Characters also do not generally start with much. Through playing, your character will have opportunities to improve their equipment but typically start with a few basics. Roll 2d6 and add your Background's RP Bonus for your starting RP amount. If you roll doubles, roll your Chance Die, and add it to the result. [See Chapter 7: The Armory, for more RP rules, and equipment.]</p> <p>That said, with every Background is a list of possible starting benefits. A player may pick 1 of these benefits to go along with the other, automatic benefits of their Background. Optionally, the player may also roll 2d6 to randomly determine their starting benefit. The player may choose or roll another benefit at Levels 4, 8, 12, 16, and 20.</p>"},{"location":"character-creation/#athlete","title":"Athlete","text":"Primary Abilities: Might, Reflexes, Constitution Starting Health: 10 + Constitution + 3d6 Starting RP: +40 Weapon Groups: Brawling, Light Melee Add 1 to your Reflexes Ability Pick one of the following Traits: Athletic (Might, Reflexes, or Constitution), Acrobatics (Reflexes), Running (Constitution), or Climbing (Might)"},{"location":"character-creation/#athlete-starting-benefits","title":"Athlete Starting Benefits","text":"2d6 Benefit 2 +1 Constitution 3-4 Trait: Martial Arts (Might or Reflexes) 5 Trait: Swimming (Constitution) 6 Trait: Strength (Might) 7-8 +1 Reflexes 9 Weapon Group: Archaic Ranged 10-11 +1 Might 12 Weapon Group: Archaic Melee"},{"location":"character-creation/#blue-collar","title":"Blue Collar","text":"Primary Abilities: Might, Constitution, Wits Starting Health: 10 + Constitution + 2d6 Starting RP: +40 Weapon Groups: Light Melee, Heavy Melee Add 1 to your Constitution Ability Pick one of the following Traits: Strength (Might), Jury-Rigging (Wits), or Driving (Reflexes)"},{"location":"character-creation/#blue-collar-starting-benefits","title":"Blue Collar Starting Benefits","text":"2d6 Benefit 2 +1 Might 3-4 Trait: Smithing (Might) 5 Trait: Electrical (Wits) 6 Trait: Engineering (Wits) 7-8 +1 Wits 9 Weapon Group: Crafting (Reflexes) 10-11 Lock-Picking (Reflexes) 12 +1 Reflexes"},{"location":"character-creation/#law-enforcement","title":"Law Enforcement","text":"Primary Abilities: Might, Reflexes, Perception Starting Health: 10 + Constitution + 2d6 Starting RP: +50 Weapon Groups: Brawling, Light Melee, Small-Arms Add 1 to your Perception Ability Pick one of the following Traits: Running (Constitution), Persuasion (Willpower), or Leadership (Willpower)"},{"location":"character-creation/#law-enforcement-starting-benefits","title":"Law Enforcement Starting Benefits","text":"2d6 Benefit 2 +1 Constitution 3-4 Trait: Martial Arts (Might or Reflexes) 5 Trait: Willpower (Bargaining) 6 Trait: Research (Wits) 7-8 +1 Might 9 Traits: Military Lore (Wits) 10-11 +1 Willpower 12 +1 Expertise"},{"location":"character-creation/#medicine","title":"Medicine","text":"Primary Abilities: Wits, Willpower, Perception Starting Health: 10 + Constitution + 2d6 Starting RP: +80 Weapon Groups: none Add 1 to your Willpower Ability Traits: Empathy (Perception), Natural Lore (Wits), Healing (Wits)"},{"location":"character-creation/#medicine-starting-benefits","title":"Medicine Starting Benefits","text":"2d6 Benefit 2 +1 Wits 3-4 Trait: Searching (Perception) 5 Trait: Historical Lore (Wits) 6 Trait: Surgery (Willpower) 7-8 +1 Constitution 9 Trait: Courage (Willpower) 10-11 Trait: Self-Discipline (Willpower) 12 +1 Willpower"},{"location":"character-creation/#military","title":"Military","text":"Primary Abilities: Might, Reflexes, Willpower Starting Health: 10 + Constitution + 3d6 Starting RP: +60 Weapon Groups: pick to between: Light Melee, Heavy Melee, Small-Arms, Long-Arms, Heavy-Arms, Stealth Weapons Add 1 to your Might Ability Pick one of the following Traits: Courage (Willpower), Knives (Reflexes), Martial-Arts (Might), Grappling (Might or Reflexes), Basic Training (Any)"},{"location":"character-creation/#military-starting-benefits","title":"Military Starting Benefits","text":"2d6 Benefit 2 +1 Constitution 3-4 Trait: Stealth (Reflexes) 5 Trait: Explosives Lore (Wits) 6 Trait: Courage (Willpower) 7-8 +1 Willpower 9 Self-Discipline (Willpower) 10-11 +1 Perception 12 +1 Expertise"},{"location":"character-creation/#scholar","title":"Scholar","text":"Primary Abilities: Wits, Willpower, Perception Starting Health: 10 + Constitution + 1d6 Starting RP: +30 Weapon Groups: none Add 2 to your Wits Ability Traits: Computer Use (Wits), Cryptography (Wits), Research (Wits)"},{"location":"character-creation/#scholar-starting-benefits","title":"Scholar Starting Benefits","text":"2d6 Benefit 2 +1 Willpower 3-4 Trait: Faith (Willpower) 5 Trait: Crafting (Reflexes) 6 Trait: Electrical (Wits) 7-8 +1 Perception 9 Trait: Stamina (Constitution) 10-11 Trait: Cultural Lore (Wits) 12 +1 Wits"},{"location":"character-creation/#white-collar","title":"White Collar","text":"Primary Abilities: Wits, Perception, Willpower Starting Health: 10 + Constitution + 1d6 Starting RP: +120 Weapon Groups: none Add 1 to your Willpower Ability Traits: Bargaining (Wits or Willpower), Etiquette (Willpower), Evaluation (Wits)"},{"location":"character-creation/#white-collar-starting-benefits","title":"White Collar Starting Benefits","text":"2d6 Benefit 2 +1 Willpower 3-4 Trait: Morale (Willpower) 5 Trait: Persuasion (Willpower) 6 Trait: Writing (Wits) 7-8 +1 Wits 9 Traits: Deception (Willpower or Wits) 10-11 Traits: Empathy (Perception) 12 +1 Reflexes Optional Starting Traits <p>Need more flexibility in your background? Ask your GM about these optional Background Bonuses. Note that picking one of these replaces the Starting Benefit (at minimum) of the Background you've chosen.</p> <ul> <li> <p>Improv Expert: Once per Rest, pick a number of Traits you do not have equal to your Wits Ability, gaining a +2 bonus, as though they would in a Secondary Ability.</p> </li> <li> <p>Student of All: Instead of gaining the default benefits of your Background, pick a single element from each of the available Backgrounds to start with.</p> </li> <li> <p>Basic Training: Any time you would gain the Basic Tier of an Expertise, you may gain an additional Basic Tier of another Expertise.</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"core-rules/","title":"Chapter 2: Rules of Engagement","text":""},{"location":"core-rules/#implements-of-fate","title":"Implements of Fate","text":"<p>These are the tools you will need for play.</p>"},{"location":"core-rules/#players","title":"Players:","text":"<p>Players only need three things to be ready for play. With the right foreknowledge on the character concept you'd like to play, a character sheet can be completely filled out in as little as five to ten minutes. Which, with the brutality inherent in this system, could potentially be important.</p> <ol> <li>Three six-sided die (3d6). Two of a single color , and a third of a contrasting color (or design). We'll discuss why a little later in this chapter.</li> <li>A pencil (or pen, if you like to live dangerously.) to adjust elements of your character.</li> <li>A character sheet, to hold all of your character's items, weapons, and abilities for reference.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"core-rules/#game-masters","title":"Game Masters:","text":"<p>A Game Master (GM) won't need much more than their players. The GM, however, does have a lot more optional tools at their disposal.</p> <p>Needed:</p> <ol> <li>A physical or digital copy of this book.</li> <li>At least 3d6. Again, two of a single color, and a third of a contrasting color (or design).</li> <li>A single ten-sided die (d10).</li> <li>An Adventure (a few sample adventures have been provided in Chapter 9 of this book. Feel free to mix, match, and mash-up to your heart's content).</li> </ol> <p>Optional</p> <ol> <li>A GM Screen. Some prefer the secrecy and natural tension provided by the GM screen. Others let the dice fall where they may, for all to see, and let their player's demises be recognized before they announce them.</li> <li>A second ten-sided die (d10), should you desire to roll percentile chance situations, create/use d100 lists.</li> <li>Maps and/or minis.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"core-rules/#abilities-and-how-to-use-them","title":"Abilities and How to Use Them","text":""},{"location":"core-rules/#a-brief-explanation-of-abilities","title":"A Brief Explanation of Abilities","text":"<p>There are six Ability scores, split between physical and mental prowess, listed below. The Average adult human's score is 0.</p> <p>Throughout play you'll improve your skills, gaining Traits, Expertise, Specializations, and other abilities. Many of these modify the rolls you make with your Ability Scores, as bonuses and penalties.</p> Might This ability represents your character's physical strength. It covers such things as lifting heavy objects, carrying a friend, or grappling a foe. Reflexes This ability represents your character's general dexterity and is used to determine how hard they are to hit, whether through speed or effective movement through cover. Constitution This ability represents your character's health, endurance, and resistance to the physical dangers of the world. Wits This ability represents your character's acquired wealth of knowledge. It is useful in recalling information, planning, and understanding complex situations. Willpower This ability represents your character's applied experiences. It is a key component in applying one's skills to varying situations. Perception This ability represents your character's senses and hand-eye coordination."},{"location":"core-rules/#action-rolls","title":"Action Rolls","text":"<p>3d6 + Ability + Trait</p> <p>Whenever you want to do something, aside from basic movement and conversation, your GM is likely to ask you to make an Action Roll. Everything else in the game derives from the Action Roll. From firing a weapon, to driving a vehicle, to finding that key you dropped under the refrigerator.</p> <p>During play, your GM will set the scene and then open the floor to the players who decide how to interact with what\u2019s been described.</p> <p>Dice are only necessary when there is a significant consequence for performing (or failing) an action.</p> <p>To make an Action Roll, roll your 3d6. Two dice should be one color and the third a different color. The contrasting die is called the Chance Die. Add your relevant Ability Score, and an additional 2 if you have a related Trait, although the Trait is not necessary to attempt the roll. The final number is your test result, which you want to meet or exceed your Challenge Rating.</p> <p>Even if you have several Traits that could apply, you can only use one on a test. You can never gain the benefits of more than one Trait on an Action Roll. These results are compared, either to a Challenge Rating set by the GM, or set by an opponent rolling against you.</p>"},{"location":"core-rules/#action-roll","title":"Making an Action Roll","text":"<p>When it is time to make a test, you are either rolling against a fixed Challenge Rating (CR) determined by the GM based on assumed difficulty, or an opponent's roll.</p> <ol> <li>You tell the GM what you are trying to do.</li> <li>The GM determines the ability and applicable Trait (if any). They then assign a CR to the task based on its difficulty and the prevailing circumstances.</li> <li>You make an Action Roll and figure out your result.</li> <li>If your test result is equal to or greater than the CR, you have successfully completed your action as intended.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"core-rules/#difficulty","title":"Difficulty","text":"<p>The following table provides a common perception for test difficulty.</p> <p>Also listed below are Advanced Action Rolls. These are provided for determining the effective Threat Level of non-combat situations, or for GMs who like to determine whether partial success or failure can apply to a roll.</p> <p>Standard Task Difficulty</p> Difficulty CR Trivial: 7 Simple: 9 Average: 11 Challenging: 13 Hard: 15 Severe: 17 Imposing: 19 Near Impossible: 21 <p>Advanced Task Difficulty (Success Threshold)</p> Difficulty Threshold Trivial: \u2264 5 Simple: 6-8 Moderate: 9-12 Difficult: 13-16 Professional: \u2265 17"},{"location":"core-rules/#advantage-and-disadvantage","title":"Advantage and Disadvantage","text":"<p>At times, your GM may decide a roll has been particularly affected by your circumstances. At that time, they will inform the player that their character has a minor or Major Advantage or Disadvantage. Following are the bonus(es)/penalty(ies) and examples.</p> <p>2 or more sources of Minor Advantage/Disadvantage becomes a Major Advantage/Disadvantage. On the other hand, regardless of number, Major Advantages/Disadvantages do not stack in this way, although multiple instances and sources count when determining whether or not an Advantage or Disadvantage cancels its opposite out.</p> <p>Minor Advantage/Disadvantage: +2 (2-on-1, target flanked, climbing using a rope)</p> <p>Major Advantage/Disadvantage: +5 (3 or more on 1, target unaware, climbing using a ladder)</p> <p>Things to remember about Action Rolls</p> <ul> <li>Only one Trait can apply to a Action Roll.</li> <li>Leave the dice on the table after a roll because the result of the Chance Die may be important.</li> <li>In Opposed Action Rolls, ties are broken by the higher of the total of the 2 regular dice, by the Chance Die after, or by the higher ability if the Chance Dice are tied. If all else fails, the tie will go to the defender of the action.</li> <li>For Basic Action Rolls, the GM needs to assess the situation and assign a difficulty.</li> <li>Advanced Action Rolls use a success threshold to measure completion over time, or as a rough estimate of the effective Threat Level of non-combat situations.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"core-rules/#chance-pool","title":"Chance Pool","text":"<p>As mentioned above, your off-color die is called the Chance Die. The number of Chance Points you receive is usually equal to the number that comes up on your Chance Die.</p> <p>When doubles are rolled on certain types of tests, this generates Chance Points. These points go into a pool, to be used to fuel various special maneuvers called Chance Actions.</p> <p>A Player Character's Chance Pool starts at 6 Chance Points at the beginning of every session, and caps at 18. Unused points are lost at the end of the session.</p>"},{"location":"core-rules/#combat","title":"Combat","text":"<p>When diplomacy breaks, and brutal force is the only outcome, the solution may be at the end of a barrel. For the inexperienced, this is a path to glory. For the seasoned, survival is victory enough. Yet, nothing can prepare you for the chaos of the battlefield: the deafening roar of gunfire, the thunderous shock of grenades, and the desperate cries of the wounded. In this unforgiving arena, you'll have to fight to win. To survive.</p> <p>Combat is a cornerstone of The Nomad Chronicles, defined by intense and decisive moments. At its heart of course lies the Action Roll, but when lives hang in the balance, more is required. You'll need to understand how attacks are made, how damage is dealt, and what it takes to push a character to and beyond their limits.</p>"},{"location":"core-rules/#initiative","title":"Initiative","text":"<p>Eventually, tensions will spike, and it will be important to make sense of what could be a chaotic battlefield. That's when the GM will tell the players to \"Roll for Initiative.\"</p> <p>Initiative Roll</p> <p>Initiative = Reflexes + 3d6 + Modifiers</p> <p>Once Initiative has started, time is tracked in 15-second increments called rounds. When the GM calls on you for your turn in the Initiative, you describe the various actions you'd like to attempt and roll for them. Once everyone has taken a turn, the round ends and a new one begins, until the end of the scenario that made Initiative necessary.</p> Time Conversions <p>4 rounds = 1 minute</p>"},{"location":"core-rules/#taking-actions","title":"Taking Actions","text":"<p>When it\u2019s your turn in a round, you tell the GM what you want to do. Below are listed various actions that can be taken. The list is broken down into the least involved Non-Actions to the all-important Major Actions.</p> <p>Unless otherwise stated, you can only perform one of each type of action in a round. You are not limited to the listed actions, but must discuss with your GM if what you'd like to do doesn't fall into one of these categories.</p>"},{"location":"core-rules/#non-actions","title":"Non-Actions","text":"<p>Non-Actions are activities that are done passively, don't require notable time or focus to perform, and in general consume no resources on your turn. These are often reflexive or incidental actions that flow within other actions, such as moving while speaking, or scanning the environment while standing guard.</p> MOVE: You can move up to your Speed in yards. You can also go prone, stand up, enter or exit a vehicle, but if you do so you can only move at half Speed (rounded down). If you start a round prone and do not stand up, you may only crawl, moving at half Speed. PERCEPTION CHECK: You can take a quick glance about, or listen passively in your environment without focusing on a specific detail. SHOUT!: You can make a brief, simple communication (such as a shout, warning, or command) of five words or less. CHANCE ACTION: You can use a Chance Action as an extension of a Major Action, unless otherwise described."},{"location":"core-rules/#instinct-actions","title":"Instinct Actions","text":"<p>Instinct Actions are swift, immediate responses to another character's actions, allowing you to act out of turn under specific conditions.</p> ATTACK OF OPPORTUNITY: If a target moves out of or through your melee reach, you can make a single melee attack roll against them. INTERCEPT: If an ally within 2 yards of you is attacked, you may attempt to move between the attacker and ally, redirecting the attack to yourself. QUICK DRAW: If equipped with a Quick-Draw Holster or similar, you can draw a weapon as an Instinct Action when you spot an opponent, letting you react to surprise encounters without delay."},{"location":"core-rules/#free-actions","title":"Free Actions","text":"<p>Free Actions are actions that you can perform on your turn without requiring significant time or focus.</p> QUICK DROP: Instantly release a held item, freeing up a hand. SHIFT GRIP: Change your grip on a weapon (e.g., switching from one-handed to two-handed or vice versa). SIMPLE GESTURE: Make a basic signal to an ally, such as pointing to a location or signaling to take cover. This could also be a spoken statement of about 25 words or less."},{"location":"core-rules/#minor-actions","title":"Minor Actions","text":"<p>Minor Actions are small but significant movements aimed at maneuvering skillfully around the battlefield.</p> ACTIVATE: You must use this action to start using certain Traits, such as those with the Style tag. This action also allows you to use items. AIM: You take a moment to align your next strike. If your next action is an attack, you gain a Minor Advantage (+2) bonus on your next attack roll. JUMP: You can jump from a standing or moving position. A standing high or long jump has a total distance of your Might in yards. A jump while you're moving has a total distance of your Might + Reflexes in yards. PREPARE: You pick one major action that you're prepared to use, and what will trigger it, and then end your turn. Any time until your next turn, you can interrupt another character and take your prepared action immediately as an Instinct Action. If you don\u2019t use it by your next turn, the action is lost. You can only take the Prepare action if you haven't already taken a major action. READY: You draw or holster a weapon or ready an item that was otherwise stowed for quick access. HOLD POSITION: You decide you won't be moved, planting yourself firmly. As long as you have not Moved, you can maintain Hold Position with a Minor Action for a number of Rounds equal to your Might (Strength). Any enemy who uses the Push-back or Knock Prone Chance Actions must succeed in an opposed test pitting their Might (Strength) vs. your choice of your own Might (Strength) or Reflexes (Acrobatics) in order to succeed. <p>When your opponent attempts to move you, should you win, the Chance Points they spent are still expended to no effect, regardless of how many Chance Points they spent in an attempt to move you (such as to move you more than 2 yards in a single attack with the Push-back Chance Action).</p> RUSH IN: You may move up to half your Speed (round down) in yards and then use a single Major Action. If this action is a melee attack against an adjacent enemy, you gain a +2 bonus on your melee damage total. TAKE COVER: Taking cover can be a Non-Action as part of your Initiative. Afterwards, it becomes a Minor Action if suitable cover (or a nearby object or individual) becomes readily available. The type and extent of cover provide varying levels of protection, but remember, cover might not always be practical or accessible. Choose your cover wisely, as a bullet might still have your name on it. 1/2 Cover: Gain a +2 bonus to Defense and Reflexes Saving Throws. 3/4 Cover: Gain a +5 bonus to Defense and Reflexes Saving Throws. <p>Quote</p> <p>\"They don't need to spot you to kill you, if they've got you cornered. Use cover to survive, but don't expect it to hide you forever.\" -- Captain Gil Thomas, Nomad Tactical Team 05-Bravo</p> Total Cover: You cannot be targeted by ranged attacks or abilities unless the attacker changes position or has a method to detect and bypass the cover. While in Total Cover, you may make a Blind Fire attack without exposing yourself. This attack suffers Major Disadvantage (-5), and cannot use Chance Actions or Chance Breaks. However, you may still benefit from the Chance Die, representing a lucky or instinctual hit. Attacking from Total Cover allows enemies to guess your position. If you did not Move when taking cover, an attacker may roll a Perception (Empathy) check vs your Reflexes (Stealth). On a success, they may attempt a single attack against you as though you had 3/4 Cover. <p>For detailed rules on using items and individuals as cover, refer to Chapter 6: The Armory.</p> Tip <p>In order to use an individual as improvised cover, the aggressor must first be in control of a grapple. The target character must be Entangled or Helpless in order to be used as cover. If an attack is made, and would miss the controlling character by 5 or less points, the attack hits the hostage used as cover, dealing normal damage to them.</p> <p>Cover Table</p> Cover Type Defense &amp; Save Bonus Other Effect 1/2 Cover +2 - 3/4 Cover +5 - Total Cover Cannot be targeted directly Blind Fire only (\u20135), no Chance Actions/Breaks. Can be targeted as 3/4 Cover if attacker succeeds on Perception (Empathy) vs Reflexes (Stealth) and the target did not Move."},{"location":"core-rules/#major-actions","title":"Major Actions","text":"<p>Major Actions are substantial, requiring the majority of your focus and time within a turn, like attacking or interacting with complex objects.</p> AID: You take a moment to assist an ally, granting them a Minor Advantage (+2) on a single Action Roll (combat or ability). BLIND FIRE: You throw caution to the wind, firing at your target without fully assessing their position. You suffer a Major Disadvantage (-5) to the attack roll, and cannot use Chance Actions or Chance Breaks with the attack. DEFEND: You brace yourself for incoming attacks, focusing entirely on self-preservation. Until the start of your next turn, you gain a +2 bonus to your Defense. GRAPPLE: You make a Melee Attack roll against an adjacent enemy. If you succeed, you and your target then engage in an opposed Might Action Roll. Success in this test grants you control of the grapple, applying the Entangled Condition to your target. While you control the grapple, you may: <ol> <li> <p>Choke: Invoke an additional opposed Might Action Roll. On a success, target gains 1 Tier of the Winded Condition. A choke can be held using a Minor Action at the start of each new turn the target hasn't escaped. Each turn the choke is held increases the Winded Condition by 1 Tier.</p> </li> <li> Strike: Attack your target with an Unarmed attack or a light, one-handed weapon you possess or can draw. Targeting the Entangled Character: The attack is made with a Minor Advantage due to the close proximity. The penalty for Called Shots is reduced by one step (from Major Disadvantage to Minor Disadvantage, or from Minor Disadvantage to a standard roll). Targeting the Completely Restrained Character: The attack is made with a Major Advantage. The penalty for Called Shots is eliminated, and the attack is more likely to hit due to the target's vulnerability. </li> <li> <p>Lock: Invoke an additional opposed Might Action Roll. On a success, the target gains an additional Tier of the Entangled Condition.</p> </li> <li> <p>Drag: Invoke an additional opposed Might Action Roll. Success here allows you to travel up to half of your Movement Speed while maintaining the grapple. This Action Roll is automatically successful on a Subdued target.</p> </li> <li> Ranged Attack: While grappling, you can use a Major Action to make a Ranged Attack (not affected by Expertise or Expertise) against your target or another enemy within range. Targeting the Entangled Character: The attack is made with a Minor Advantage due to the close proximity. The penalty for Called Shots is reduced by one step (from Major Disadvantage to Minor Disadvantage, or from Minor Disadvantage to a standard roll). Targeting the Completely Restrained Character: The attack is made with a Major Advantage. The penalty for Called Shots is eliminated, and the attack is more likely to hit due to the target's vulnerability. Targeting Another Character: The attack is made with a Minor Disadvantage (-2) due to the difficulty of aiming accurately while engaged in close combat. </li> <li> <p>Throw: Invoke an additional Might Action Roll. Success here throws your target a number of yards equal to half your Might score, dealing damage based on the AP value of whatever they hit.</p> </li> </ol> <p>Both you and your target suffer a -2 penalty to Defense while grappling. If the target is Helpless, they suffer a -5 penalty to Defense.</p> <p>Each round, the Entangled character can attempt to break free or take control of the grapple by repeating the opposed Might Action Roll.</p> HEAL: You provide some quick first aid to an injured ally. You must be adjacent to your ally and you must have bandages ready. See the Healing section below for specific rules regarding Heal Action Rolls. <p>Failed Heal Tests</p> <p>Failing a Heal Action Roll can unfortunately make a situation much worse.  If the Action Roll is failed by 2 or more, the target of the action endures a Minor Complication, gaining a Condition appropriate to the first aid attempted.  If the Action Roll is failed by 5 or more, the target of the action endures a Major Complication, losing an amount of Health equal to the Healing character's Chance Die, and gaining 2 Conditions appropriate to the first aid attempted.  A failed Heal check can be retried, either until the target character is dead, or the Healing character succeeds, which then applies the Successful Heal Action Roll results.</p> Example <p>Theo moves to his wounded ally, pulling bandages from his medic's bag. His ally has been shot, and he's got to work fast to get the bullet out. Theo, unfortunately, gets a 9 total for his Heal Action Roll, failing the roll.</p> <p>The GM decides, based on what he was attempting, that the most appropriate condition in this situation is a level of the Bleeding Condition.</p> <p>Theo attempts a second time. This time, he rolls a 5, failing the roll exceptionally. His ally takes 3 unresisted Piercing Damage, another level of Bleeding, and Nauseated Conditions, as Theo was a bit too far off with his knife placement in attempting to extract the bullet. Taking a second to breathe, calming himself from the stress, Theo tries a third time, this time succeeding with a 14.</p> <p>The ally gains the benefit of the specified Heal action, and can no longer benefit from another Heal Action Roll until taking additional damage or resting.</p> MELEE ATTACK: You attack one adjacent enemy (within 2 yards) with your fists, boots, or a hand. RANGED ATTACK: You fire or throw a missile weapon at one visible enemy within range. <p>Near Miss</p> <p>In combat, some attacks may fall just short of hitting, but still have an effect on the target. If an attack roll misses, but is within 2 points of a character's Defense, the attack technically hits, but does the minimum amount of damage possible, to a minimum of 1.\"</p> SPRINT: You can move up to double your Speed in yards. You cannot take this action if you are prone (you\u2019d need to use the Move action to stand up first)."},{"location":"core-rules/#attacks-damage","title":"Attacks &amp; Damage","text":"<p>Combat revolves around two primary attack types: Melee and Ranged, both resolved the same way:</p> <ol> <li>Choose a Target. Melee attacks require you to be adjacent (within 2 yards) of an opponent. Ranged attacks require line of sight and must be within your weapon's range.</li> <li>Roll to Attack. Make an Action Roll using the appropriate Ability for your weapon (e.g., Might for Archaic Melee, Perception for Firearms), modified by Traits, Expertise, and/or other relevant bonuses.</li> <li>Compare Results. Your attack roll must meet or exceed the target's Defense to hit.</li> <li>Calculate Base Damage. On a successful hit, you deal an amount of Damage equal to Weapon Damage + Ability Score.    Chance Damage (On Doubles). Whenever you roll Doubles on an attack, add your Chance Die to your Base Damage.    Critical Damage (on Triples). Whenever you roll Triples, add twice your Chance Die to your Base Damage.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"core-rules/#death-dying","title":"Death &amp; Dying","text":"<ul> <li> <p>When a PC's Health reaches 0, they begin dying, losing consciousness and perishing in 2 + Constitution in rounds unless healed. They can speak on their turn, but take no actions.</p> </li> <li> <p>Most NPCs die instantly at 0 Health, though GMs can allow PC rules for significant foes at their discretion.</p> </li> <li> <p>Health does not drop below 0 --- there are no negative Health values.</p> </li> </ul> <p>Pulling Killing Blows</p> <ul> <li>If an attacker wishes to incapacitate instead of kill with an attack that would leave a target at 0 Health, they can declare a non-lethal attack. For any weapon that does not deal bludgeoning damage, this attack is made at a Major Disadvantage (-5). A successful attack leaves the target at 1 Health, regardless of damage total, and the target suffers Stunned (T5) for 1 minute (4 rounds) or until healed.</li> </ul> <p>Delivering a Coup de Grace</p> <ul> <li> <p>A Helpless, Unconscious, or Dying character can be executed as a Major Action. The attacker forces a special Saving Throw (TN 10 + Base Damage).</p> </li> <li> <p>If the target is Helpless or Unconscious but not already Dying, failure reduces them to 0 Health and they begin Dying. Success leaves them at 1 Health but Unconscious for a duration rolled on the Downtime Chart, regardless of healing.</p> </li> <li>If the target is already Dying, they automatically fail and are killed outright.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"core-rules/#healing","title":"Healing","text":"<p>Conversely, when a character is wounded, there are several ways to be healed.</p> Immediate Care: Another character can render immediate aid as a Heal action, as described previously in this chapter. The attempting character must roll a Healing (Wits) Action Roll CR 10. Immediate Care must be applied within 1 minute (4 Rounds) of an injury occurring to be effective. You can only benefit from Immediate Care once per Rest. A successful roll on Immediate Care recovers your Constitution in Health. First-Aid Healing: You or another character can aid you with a Heal action, as described previously in this chapter. You can only benefit from First Aid twice per Rest. The attempting Character must roll a Healing (Wits) Action Roll CR 12. A successful First-Aid Healing roll recovers an amount of Health equal to the attempting character's Level. Surgery: You or another character can aid you with a Heal action, as described previously in this chapter. Note that attempting a Surgery test on yourself is done with a Major Disadvantage (-5) to the roll. The attempting character must roll a Healing (Wits) Action Roll CR 15. A successful Surgery roll adds the attempting character's Wits and your Constitution to your next Rest's recovery amount. Failure deals damage to the target equal to what the recovery would have been. Surgery is one of the only ways to heal certain Conditions. Breather: You can take a 5 to 10-minute break after a combat encounter. After a breather, you get back 2 + Constitution in Health. The benefits of a Breather only occur once after an encounter's end, and not at all if you ended the encounter at 0 Health. Rest: You take 6-10 hours of minimal activity, focusing on your own recovery. If you can get at least 6 hours of rest, you heal 5 + Constitution in Health. Professional Medical Care: Being cared for in a professional medical environment grants significant benefits to healing. Most notably, a +2 bonus to Health recovery for every Rest."},{"location":"expertise/","title":"Chapter 4: Particulars of Expertise","text":""},{"location":"expertise/#traits","title":"Traits","text":"<p>What a Trait Represents</p> <p>A Trait represents focused training or experience, not raw talent. As such:</p> <ul> <li>Traits do not grant new actions unless explicitly stated.</li> <li>Traits provide a situational bonus to Action Rolls where applicable.</li> <li>Traits may be referenced by other rules (Expertise, Chance Actions, Equipment), but are not locked to them (if another Trait could apply, speak to your GM).</li> <li>Traits never stack with other Traits on the same Action Roll.</li> </ul> <p>A Trait is a focused area of proficiency within its related ability. A Trait placed in a Primary Ability grants a +3 bonus when making an Action Roll related to it. This bonus is only a +2 for Secondary Ability Traits. The GM will usually let you know what Trait applies to each test, but if it isn't clear don't be afraid to ask if a Trait applies.</p> <p>Starting at Level 11, you may select a Trait you already have, to increase your bonus with it by 1. This increases Primary Ability Traits to a +4, and Secondary Ability Traits to a +3.</p> <p>Variable Traits are those that don't fit cleanly into any single category. When you take a Trait in the Variable list, you can apply it to one of your Ability Scores. You must be able to justify your use of a Trait should your choice be questionable. Be sure to discuss these with your GM to determine.</p> Creating Unique Traits <p>If a GM or Player can justify the creation of a Trait, feel free to do so. GM's, especially, should do this for high-profile NPCs and elite enemies.</p> <p>The primary caveat, of course, is to be sure the scope of your Trait is important enough to give you an edge, but limited in scope to keep the game fair.</p> <p>Info</p> <p>Note that Traits tagged with (Weapon Group) do not give you Weapon Group training. Weapon Group Training, however, is a prerequisite for taking one of these Traits. See #character-creation, or #equipment.</p>"},{"location":"expertise/#variable-traits","title":"Variable Traits","text":"Athletics Executing physical maneuvers, including climbing, running, and grappling. Craftsmanship Producing high-quality items. When combined with a Crafting Expertise, grants an additional Minor Advantage (+2) on the Test. Intimidation Influencing others through threats, posture, or sheer presence. Light Melee (Weapon Group) Fighting with weapons from the Light Melee group, often usable with either Might or Reflexes. Multitasking Managing multiple actions simultaneously. Once per encounter, gain an additional Minor Action. Profession Performing specialized career or trade-oriented tasks."},{"location":"expertise/#might-traits","title":"Might Traits","text":"Archaic Melee (Weapon Group) Fighting with melee weapons from pre-modern eras. Climbing Scaling vertical surfaces and overcoming obstacles. Heavy Melee (Weapon Group) Fighting with large, high-impact melee weapons. Improvised Melee (Weapon Group) Fighting with handheld objects not designed as weapons. Jumping Covering distance through leaps and vaults. Martial Arts (Weapon Group) Fighting Unarmed, using trained techniques and specialized stances. Smithing Forging and shaping metal into weapons, armor, and tools. Strength Performing feats of raw power, such as lifting, carrying, or breaking objects."},{"location":"expertise/#reflexes-traits","title":"Reflexes Traits","text":"Acrobatics Performing gymnastic maneuvers, balancing, and tumbling. Archaic Ranged (Weapon Group) Fighting with ranged weapons from pre-modern eras. Calligraphy Writing with precision and artistic flair. CQB Using ranged weapons effectively in melee combat. Crafting Making items with precise manual skills like woodworking, sculpting, glassblowing, etc. Driving Directing and guiding motorized ground or naval vehicles. Initiative Acting quickly in tense situations. Lock Picking Opening locks without using keys. Piloting Directing and guiding an air vehicle. Riding Directing a mount or non-motorized wheeled vehicle. Sleight of Hand Using tricks of movement to manipulate objects in unsuspected ways. Stealth Sneaking about quietly and out of sight. Thrown Weapons (Weapon Group) Fighting with weapons that are most effective when thrown."},{"location":"expertise/#constitution-traits","title":"Constitution Traits","text":"Breath Control Keeping your breathing even and steady in situations where breathing may be difficult. Drinking Consuming larger quantities of alcohol and avoiding the after-effects. Immunity Avoiding the effects of various substances like infections and diseases. Running Moving quickly in both short sprints and long-distance hauls. Stamina Enduring fatigue and privation. Swimming Moving through liquid and staying afloat where needed."},{"location":"expertise/#wits-traits","title":"Wits Traits","text":"Brewing Making ales, wines, and other alcohol-based concoctions. Computer Use Operating a personal computer, or other device. Cryptography Creating and deciphering codes and ciphers. Cultural Lore Knowing the traditions and beliefs of various cultures. Design Planning the creation of an item. Electrical Knowing the practicalities of electrical circuits. Engineering Knowing the practicalities of mechanical construction and building. Explosives (Weapon Group) Handling, constructing, dismantling, and operating weapons from the Explosives group. Evaluation Determining the value of goods and items. Healing Aiding the wounded and sick. Heavy-Arms (Weapon Group) Fighting with specialized heavy projectile weapons. Historical Lore Knowing important events and personalities from the past. Jury-Rigging Knowing how to build temporary items to perform specific tasks. Military Lore Knowing music theory, tradition, and songs. Natural Lore Knowing flora and fauna, and their potential uses. Navigation Planning and following a route from one place to another. Poison Lore Knowing about poisonous substances, their uses, and their preparation. Research Making a systematic investigation, usually using records, archives, and books. Religious Lore Knowing religious traditions and practices. Writing Expressing yourself with the written word."},{"location":"expertise/#willpower-traits","title":"Willpower Traits","text":"Animal Handling Interacting with and caring for animals. Bargaining Negotiating with others and making deals. Courage Maintaining personal confidence and refusing to succumb to fear effects. Deception Lying to and tricking others using fast talk and subterfuge. Etiquette Knowing the social niceties of various cultures. Faith Deriving inner strength through spiritual or moral belief. Leadership Guiding, directing, and inspiring others. Morale Maintaining good spirits and confidence in yourself or your group. Performance Entertaining an audience with an artistic expertise. Persuasion Convincing others to agree with you. Self-Discipline Focusing your mental energy or controlling your impulses and emotions."},{"location":"expertise/#perception-traits","title":"Perception Traits","text":"Empathy Discerning the feelings, emotions, and intentions of others. Hearing Using your auditory sense to notice and identify things. Improvised Range (Weapon Group) Fighting with projectile-launching objects not normally classified as weapons. Long-Arms (Weapon Group) Fighting with long-barelled firearms. Searching Finding things that are hidden or obscured. Seeing Using your visual sense to notice and identify things. Small-Arms (Weapon Group) Fighting with small hand-held firearms. Smelling Using your olfactory sense to notice and identify things. Tracking Following footprints and other signs of passage through an area. <p>Info</p> <p>The Bargaining, Leadership, and Profession Traits each multiply RP gained from monthly wages, leveling, and missions; by 2, 3, or 4, depending on Trait level and whether the trait is Primary or Secondary. The benefits from these Traits do not stack.</p>"},{"location":"expertise/#working-in-multiple-disciplines","title":"Working in Multiple Disciplines","text":"<p>Cross-Training at a Glance</p> <ul> <li>Gain the benefits of a second Background</li> <li>Recieve:<ul> <li>1 Weapon Group (if available)</li> <li>1 Background Benefit</li> <li>+10 RP Income</li> </ul> </li> <li>Can be taken twice (with expanded options at Level 11+)</li> </ul> <p>Some people career hop. Some go into dual-degree programs. There isn't a one-size-fits-all categorization of background experiences. Since the backgrounds in TNC function effectively like classes in other systems, and being trained for various applications of skill is a real-life experience, these Traits operate outside of the normal Trait rules. Like Variable Traits, these can potentially fit under multiple Abilities, and can therefore be listed under any of them.</p> <p>Instead of the normal bonus gained by taking a Trait, these options allow you to pick up an additional Background, and grant you the following from the chosen secondary Background: 1 Weapon Group Training (if available), 1 chosen Background Benefit, and their monthly RP earnings increases by +10 for leveling and monthly income purchases. If taken a second time at or beyond level 11, the PC can acquire 1 additional Background training, using the above rules, which stack with the first. Alternatively, they can gain 1 additional Background benefit from their first cross-training, and their RP earnings increase by another (for a maximum of +20). This does not affect Mission income.</p>"},{"location":"expertise/#cross-training-traits","title":"Cross-Training Traits","text":"Athlete Training Blue Collar Training Law Enforcement Training Medicine Training Military Training Scholar Training White Collar Training"},{"location":"expertise/#expertise_1","title":"Expertise","text":"<p>Expertise is what separates the commanders from their rank-and-file counterparts. As characters grow in their abilities, it's likely they'll specialize in mastering their disciplines. Prerequisite training required to begin training in an expertise is indicated in its block.</p> <p>Each Expertise comes in four tiers, which must be taken in order: Basic, which covers the bare minimum of training required to use an Expertise's abilities. Initiate, which indicates a moderate level of training. Advanced, which is the point at which mastery begins to truly show. And, finally, Expert, which indicates true, full mastery in a given Expertise.</p> <p>The Expertise listed are separated into categories, indicating how they would most likely be used.</p>"},{"location":"expertise/#combat","title":"Combat","text":""},{"location":"expertise/#exp-agile-defense-style","title":"Agile Defense Style","text":"<p>Prerequisites: Trained in Martial Arts; No Equipped Armor</p> <p>Defense is not optional for you\u2026</p> OverviewBasicInitiateAdvancedExpert <p>Role: Reactive defense and counter-pressure</p> <p>Playstyle: Stay mobile, bait attacks, punish mistakes</p> <p>When an attack is made against you, you gain +2 Defense and your Speed increases by 1 + \u00bd level (rounded down) yards.</p> <p>Using the Defend Minor Action while in melee grants\u2026</p> <ul> <li>Swift-Shift (1 CP): Use Defend as an Instinct Action.</li> <li>Brutal Counter (2 CP): If an enemy misses\u2026</li> </ul> <ul> <li>Defense bonus increases to +5.</li> <li>Only The Strong: If an enemy misses\u2026</li> </ul>"},{"location":"intro/","title":"Introduction","text":""},{"location":"intro/#the-nomad-initiative","title":"The Nomad Initiative","text":"<p>Service in honor. Hope in Brotherhood. Victory in Sacrifice. This is what it means to be a Nomad. The Nomad Initiative began as an experimental military unit comprised of otherwise ordinary people intentionally infected with what is known as the Nano-Virus.</p> <p>The Nano-Virus enhances the human body beyond its normal limits. It provides some with additional strength, resilience, or speed. As such, it turned its initial units into powerful weapons of war. But, as with all experiments, there were side effects. Some that were infected failed to assimilate the virus correctly, becoming grotesque and dangerous creatures.</p> <p>The program was eventually scrapped by the military, but its creator continued in secret, perfecting his creation.  Survivors of that initial program have become parents. And, unknown to those in command, many of their progeny carry a successful iteration of the virus within their blood.</p>"},{"location":"intro/#what-to-expect","title":"What to Expect","text":"<p>The Nomad Chronicles system assumes a modern level of technology, with a little dabble into future tech. Power armor exists but is extremely experimental. Only a few suits exist, and they're jealously guarded. Handheld frictionless railgun weapons as well.</p> <p>For the most part, however, whatever you can find in the modern world, you should have access to in this system. The core of the Nomad Chronicles is an exploration of survival, resilience, friendship, and struggling with your inner demons. Players and Game Masters (GMs) are encouraged to explore these themes in their games. Though, as with all systems; rules, themes, and other such situations, are guidelines secondary to your enjoyment of the game.</p> <p>Given the history behind the Nomad Initiative and the Nano-Virus, quite a few kinds of stories are possible using this system. Perhaps the players are recruits in a black-ops unit tasked with overthrowing a nation. Perhaps they're college friends starting their own mercenary outfit. Or, as in the initial Nomad novel, they could even be attempting to survive in the event of a large-scale failed infection.</p> <p>In all cases, it's likely the players will need to emphasize teamwork, strategy, and creative problem-solving. At times, it will take that and more to succeed in the mission.</p>"},{"location":"intro/#the-structure","title":"The Structure","text":"<p>The mechanics for this system are loosely based on the Adventure Game Engine (AGE) 3d6 ruleset. Let's take a moment or two to address how this system differs, is structured, and how to use it. Because, as we all know, Tabletop Role-Playing Games (TTRPGs) are more about the application of knowledge, rather than simply having a lot of knowledge.</p> <p>System Foundations: The Nomad Chronicles (TNC) draws inspiration from the 3d6-based resolution mechanics popularized by Green Ronin Publishing's Adventure Game Engine (AGE). TNC diverges substantially, however, in mechanics, execution, and structure. - Ability Scores: TNC uses six core abilities with a unique range and scaling, as opposed to AGE's nine core abilities. - Action Resolution: While both systems use 3d6, TNC introduces the Chance Die, that feeds from and interacts with a persistent Chance Pool for tactical ability use rather than triggering immediate-use Chance Actions. - Progression: TNC features Experience Points and Survivor Points for advancement, allowing granular character growth through ability improvements, Traits, gear proficiencies, infection level, and mutations. - Traits &amp; Expertise: TNC separates Traits (small bonuses) from deep, multi-tiered Expertise, creating a hybrid between class features and skill trees. - Combat: :: TNC emphasizes cinematic, condition-based combat with custom mechanics for cover, knockback, mutation states, and tactical positioning. - Thematic Setting: While the concept of super soldiers is nothing new to fiction, the viral nature of the Nomads, alongside item degradation, Requisition Points (RP), and narrative \"Virus Mode\" moments, provides a wholly distinct flavor and gameplay experience.test  test  test  test  test </p>"},{"location":"_entries/expertise/exp-agile-defense-style/","title":"Exp agile defense style","text":""},{"location":"_entries/expertise/exp-agile-defense-style/#exp-agile-defense-style","title":"Agile Defense Style","text":"<p>Prerequisites: Trained in Martial Arts; No Equipped Armor</p> <p>Defense is not optional for you\u2026</p> OverviewBasicInitiateAdvancedExpert <p>Role: Reactive defense and counter-pressure</p> <p>Playstyle: Stay mobile, bait attacks, punish mistakes</p> <p>When an attack is made against you, you gain +2 Defense and your Speed increases by 1 + \u00bd level (rounded down) yards.</p> <p>Using the Defend Minor Action while in melee grants\u2026</p> <ul> <li>Swift-Shift (1 CP): Use Defend as an Instinct Action.</li> <li>Brutal Counter (2 CP): If an enemy misses\u2026</li> </ul> <ul> <li>Defense bonus increases to +5.</li> <li>Only The Strong: If an enemy misses\u2026</li> </ul>"}]}
>>>>>>> 31f79e9 (Updated Homepage, Rulebook, Digital Character Sheet)
